result.execSummary:
The defendant Jonathan M Parr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/Intent-Heroin(>3-10g) [Modifiers: Party to a Crime, Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(d)2.
  • Possess w/Intent-Cocaine (>1-5g) [Modifiers: Party to a Crime, Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(cm)1r.

Defendant Jonathan M Parr in court with attorney Munjed A. Ahmad.  Brandon Wigley for Danielle Chojnacki appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Sentencing proceeded. Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Additional Statements: Veronica P. 
AS TO COUNT 3:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 9 YEARS, concurrent to Count 4 and consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 3 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 5 YEARS.  
AS TO COUNT 4:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 9 YEARS, concurrent to Count 3 and consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 3 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 5 YEARS.  
Defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program. 
Court STAYED the sentences and placed defendant on probation for 4 YEARS with the following conditions:
AS TO COUNT 3 AND 4 THE CONDITIONS OF PROBATION and/or EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety, no alcohol.
- No use or possession of controlled substances without a valid 
  prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  and successfully complete recommended treatment
  including drug and alcohol testing. 
- Mental Health Evaluation and any recommended treatment.
- No possession of any drug paraphernalia for personal use, distributing, manufacturing or delivering. 
- No possession of any firearms or weapons, firearm ammunition, firearm case or holster, or any body armor. Defendant may not be present or reside in any residence where any of these items are present. 
- Complete literacy GED or HSED program.
- Seek and maintain full time work and/or school.
- Complete paternity testing. 
- Court ordered Defendant to comply with all child support court orders.
- Complete parenting class. 
- Curfew for the first 12 months is from 8 p.m. to 8 a.m. with the exception of verified work hours or activities approved by probation agent. 
- No contact with the residence of 2109 W Lapham Street, Milwaukee, WI.
- Court prohibits contact with Devonte B. (D.O.B. 4/28/1992)during confinement and during Extended Supervision.
- No contact with any person or place where drugs are being illegally sold or used. 
- As to both COUNT 3 and 4: Pay all mandatory court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including
  the DNA surcharge, during the course of probation to the probation agent. 
  Any remaining balance due at the end of probation will become immediately due
  or civil judgment to be entered. Any cash bail on deposit to apply, and any remaining is to be returned       
  to the remitter. 
-Provide a DNA sample, if not already done. 
AS TO COUNT 3 AND 4 AS A CONDITION OF PROBATION:
Defendant sentenced to serve 10 MONTHS condition time in the House of Correction, without good time; with release to the Day Reporting Center ONLY. Court notes a strong objection to Electronic Monitoring for the first 5 months. Court has no objection to electronic monitoring after the first 5 months if there is successful participation in the Day Reporting Center, if no participation than the strong objection to electronic monitoring continues.  
Court approved participation in Dosage Probation Pilot Program and early termination of probation if defendant successfully completes program and all other conditions of probation.
Defense requests a stay on the report date for condition time. Arguments heard. Court denies the requests for a report in date for the reason placed on the record. Condition time to begin forthwith. 

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.

Court advises the Defendant that under Wisconsin Statute 302.113 the amount actually served may be extended, and that the Defendant could serve the entire bifurcated sentence in prison. The Defendant will be subject to certain conditions while on release to extended supervision, and a violation of any of those conditions may result in the Defendant being returned to prison.

Defendant Jonathan M Parr in court with attorney Munjed A. Ahmad.  Danielle E. Chojnacki appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
  Deputy court clerk ccp.
Case set for jury trial. Parties have reached a resolution in this matter. Amended information was previously filed on 10/14/14. Defendant charged as follows:

COUNT 3- Possession with Intent to Deliver Controlled Substance (Heroin) (>3-10 grams) - PTAC, As a Party to a Crime, Use of a Dangerous Weapon, contrary to sec. 961.41(1m)(d)2, 939.50(3)(e), 939.05 Wis. Stats., a Class E Felony. 

COUNT 4- Possession with Intent to Deliver Cocaine (<=5G) - PTAC< as a Party to a Crime, Use of a Dangerous Weapon, contrary to sec. 961.41(1m)(cm)1r, 939.50(3)(f), 939.05 Wis. Stats., a Class F Felony. 

Plea hearing proceeded. 
As to COUNT 3 as amended and COUNT 4 as amended-
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgments of conviction entered.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court also advises defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  
Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing.

Court ordered a Presentence Investigation report with a recommendation. Case adjourned to Branch 17.
